1
00:00:43,502 --> 00:00:44,920
(SIGHING)

2
00:00:46,713 --> 00:00:49,841
(MERRY CHRISTMAS EVERYBODY BY SLADE
PLAYING ON RADIO)

3
00:00:49,925 --> 00:00:51,843
(CLANGING)

4
00:00:51,927 --> 00:00:53,637
Turn that down.

5
00:00:53,720 --> 00:00:56,807
Turn it off, Steve, man. Turn it off!
John, shut up!

6
00:00:58,475 --> 00:01:00,477
(DISTANT WHOOSHING)

7
00:01:05,732 --> 00:01:06,942
Rose!

8
00:01:17,619 --> 00:01:19,788
-Mickey!
-Jackie, it's the Tardis.

9
00:01:19,871 --> 00:01:22,082
I know, I know. I heard it.
She's alive, Mickey.

10
00:01:22,165 --> 00:01:24,084
I said so, didn't I? She's alive!

11
00:01:24,167 --> 00:01:26,837
MICKEY: Just shut up a minute.
JACKIE: Where is it, then?

12
00:01:34,219 --> 00:01:35,721
(JACKIE SCREAMS)

13
00:01:42,769 --> 00:01:47,274
Here we are, then.
London, Earth, the solar system, isn't it?

14
00:01:50,068 --> 00:01:53,989
Jackie, Mickey, blimey!
No, no, no, no. Hold on.

15
00:01:54,448 --> 00:01:57,409
Wait there. What was I going to say?

16
00:01:57,492 --> 00:02:00,621
There was something I had to tell you.
Something important. What was it?

17
00:02:00,704 --> 00:02:02,372
No, hold on. Hold on. Hold on.

18
00:02:02,456 --> 00:02:03,915
(SHUSHING)

19
00:02:04,416 --> 00:02:06,043
Oh! I know.

20
00:02:06,126 --> 00:02:07,669
(PANTING)

21
00:02:08,629 --> 00:02:09,963
Merry Christmas!

22
00:02:13,216 --> 00:02:15,886
-What happened? Is he all right?
-I don't know. He just keeled over.

23
00:02:15,969 --> 00:02:18,889
-But who is he? Where's the Doctor?
-That's him.

24
00:02:18,972 --> 00:02:22,142
Right in front of you. That's the Doctor.

25
00:02:22,225 --> 00:02:25,437
What do you mean, that's the Doctor?
Doctor who?

26
00:02:26,229 --> 00:02:28,774
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

27
00:03:09,398 --> 00:03:13,610
Here we go. Tina the cleaner's
got this lodger, medical student.

28
00:03:13,694 --> 00:03:16,113
And she was fast asleep so I just took it.

29
00:03:16,238 --> 00:03:17,989
I still say we should take him to hospital.

30
00:03:18,073 --> 00:03:20,575
We can't. They'd lock him up.
They'd dissect him.

31
00:03:20,659 --> 00:03:23,078
One bottle of his blood
could change the future of the human race.

32
00:03:23,203 --> 00:03:24,621
No... Shh.

33
00:03:34,631 --> 00:03:36,717
(HEART BEATING)

34
00:03:41,471 --> 00:03:43,473
(HEART BEATING)

35
00:03:43,598 --> 00:03:45,892
-Both working.
-What do you mean, both?

36
00:03:45,976 --> 00:03:48,854
-Well, he's got two hearts.
-Oh, don't be stupid.

37
00:03:48,937 --> 00:03:50,313
He has.

38
00:03:50,397 --> 00:03:53,316
-Anything else he's got two of?
-Leave him alone.

39
00:04:17,048 --> 00:04:19,217
How can he go changing his face?

40
00:04:20,844 --> 00:04:23,263
Is that a different face
or is he a different person?

41
00:04:23,346 --> 00:04:25,348
How should I know?

42
00:04:28,518 --> 00:04:29,978
Sorry.

43
00:04:30,687 --> 00:04:33,899
The thing is, I thought I knew him, Mum.

44
00:04:35,317 --> 00:04:37,611
I thought me and him were...

45
00:04:39,738 --> 00:04:41,698
And then he goes and does this.

46
00:04:44,117 --> 00:04:46,578
I keep forgetting he's not human.

47
00:04:49,998 --> 00:04:52,334
The big question is...

48
00:04:52,417 --> 00:04:55,629
where'd you get
a pair of men's pyjamas from?

49
00:04:55,712 --> 00:04:59,132
-Howard's been staying over.
-What, Howard from the market?

50
00:04:59,216 --> 00:05:01,968
-How long has that been going on?
-A month or so.

51
00:05:02,052 --> 00:05:04,721
First of all he starts delivering to the door
and I thought, "That's odd."

52
00:05:04,805 --> 00:05:06,223
(WOMAN SPEAKING ON TV)

53
00:05:06,306 --> 00:05:09,226
-Next thing you know, it's a bag of oranges.
-Is that Harriet Jones?

54
00:05:09,309 --> 00:05:11,394
-Never mind me.
-Why is she on the telly?

55
00:05:11,478 --> 00:05:15,065
She's Prime Minister now.
I'm 18 quid a week better off.

56
00:05:15,148 --> 00:05:17,651
They're calling it Britain's golden age.

57
00:05:17,734 --> 00:05:20,987
-I keep on saying my Rose has met her.
-Did more than that.

58
00:05:21,071 --> 00:05:23,240
Stopped World War III with her.

59
00:05:24,324 --> 00:05:25,534
Harriet Jones.

60
00:05:25,617 --> 00:05:28,620
What about those calling the Guinevere One
space probe a waste of money?

61
00:05:28,745 --> 00:05:32,207
Now that's where you're wrong.
I completely disagree if you don't mind.

62
00:05:32,290 --> 00:05:37,504
The Guinevere One space probe represents
this country's limitless ambition.

63
00:05:37,587 --> 00:05:40,966
British workmanship
sailing up there among the stars.

64
00:05:41,049 --> 00:05:45,220
This is the spirit of Christmas,
birth and rejoicing

65
00:05:45,303 --> 00:05:48,557
and the dawn of a new age,
and that is what we're achieving

66
00:05:48,640 --> 00:05:52,269
50 million miles away,
our very own miracle.

67
00:05:52,561 --> 00:05:54,229
COMMENTATOR:
The unmanned probe Guinevere One

68
00:05:54,312 --> 00:05:56,398
ls about to make its final descent.

69
00:05:56,481 --> 00:06:00,569
Photographs of the Martian landscape
should be received by midnight tonight.

70
00:06:18,211 --> 00:06:21,631
-So what do you need, 20 quid?
-Do you mind? I'll pay you back.

71
00:06:21,715 --> 00:06:24,426
Call it a Christmas present!

72
00:06:24,509 --> 00:06:26,303
ROSE: God, I'm all out of sync.

73
00:06:26,428 --> 00:06:28,847
You just forget about Christmas and things
in the Tardis.

74
00:06:28,972 --> 00:06:32,392
They don't exist. You get sort of...timeless.

75
00:06:32,475 --> 00:06:36,688
Oh, yeah, that's fascinating because
I love hearing stories about the Tardis.

76
00:06:36,771 --> 00:06:38,481
Ooh, go on, Rose, tell us another one

77
00:06:38,607 --> 00:06:41,526
'cause I swear I could listen to it all day,
"Tardis this, Tardis that."

78
00:06:41,610 --> 00:06:42,777
Shut up.

79
00:06:42,861 --> 00:06:46,489
"Oh, and one time the Tardis landed
in a big, yellow garden full of balloons."

80
00:06:46,615 --> 00:06:48,867
-I'm not like that.
-Oh, you so are.

81
00:06:48,992 --> 00:06:52,203
Hmm, must drive you mad.
I'm surprised you don't give up on me.

82
00:06:52,287 --> 00:06:56,124
Well, that's the thing, isn't it? You can
rely on me. I don't go changing my face.

83
00:06:56,207 --> 00:06:57,834
Yeah.

84
00:06:57,918 --> 00:06:59,669
-What if he's dying?
-Okay...

85
00:06:59,794 --> 00:07:01,379
Sorry!

86
00:07:01,546 --> 00:07:04,424
Just let it be Christmas. Can you do that?

87
00:07:05,050 --> 00:07:08,386
Just for a bit. You and me and Christmas.

88
00:07:08,470 --> 00:07:10,764
No... No Doctor.

89
00:07:10,847 --> 00:07:14,100
No bog monsters. No life or death.

90
00:07:14,184 --> 00:07:15,644
Okay.

91
00:07:15,727 --> 00:07:17,187
-Promise?
-Yes.

92
00:07:17,687 --> 00:07:20,023
Right.
What are we gonna get for your mum?

93
00:07:21,858 --> 00:07:25,278
I'm round there all the time now, you know.
She does me dinner on a Sunday...

94
00:07:25,362 --> 00:07:28,031
(MICKEY RAMBLING)

95
00:07:30,450 --> 00:07:33,036
(PLAYING GOD REST YE
MERRY GENTLEMEN)

96
00:07:49,678 --> 00:07:51,304
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

97
00:07:52,722 --> 00:07:55,016
It's us. They're after us.

98
00:08:19,791 --> 00:08:22,460
What's going on? What have we done?
Why are they after us?

99
00:08:22,544 --> 00:08:24,004
Taxi!

100
00:08:24,838 --> 00:08:26,464
They're after the Doctor.

101
00:08:26,548 --> 00:08:30,010
I can't even go shopping with you,
we get attacked by a brass band.

102
00:08:30,093 --> 00:08:31,594
-Who you phoning?
-My mum.

103
00:08:31,761 --> 00:08:35,098
She turns up, no warning.
I've got nothing in.

104
00:08:35,223 --> 00:08:39,853
I said, "Rose, if you want a Christmas
dinner of meat paste, then so be it."

105
00:08:40,228 --> 00:08:41,896
Get off the phone!

106
00:08:41,980 --> 00:08:44,065
Well, who were those...those Santa things?

107
00:08:44,149 --> 00:08:47,027
I don't know.
But think about it, they were after us.

108
00:08:47,110 --> 00:08:48,820
What's important about us? We're nothing.

109
00:08:48,945 --> 00:08:51,281
Except the one thing we've got
tucked up in bed. The Doctor.

110
00:08:51,406 --> 00:08:55,452
Oh, no, don't come round, darling.
No, the flat's all topsy-turvy.

111
00:08:55,535 --> 00:08:58,079
Yeah, she just barges in
and litters the place.

112
00:08:58,163 --> 00:09:01,291
Yeah. No, I'll come round and see you
on Boxing Day.

113
00:09:11,593 --> 00:09:14,471
-Save us a chipolata...
-Get off the phone! Get off the phone.

114
00:09:14,554 --> 00:09:16,181
It's only Bev. She says hello.

115
00:09:16,264 --> 00:09:19,225
Bev? Yeah, look, it'll have to wait.

116
00:09:20,393 --> 00:09:23,271
Right. It's not safe, we've got to get out.
Where can we go?

117
00:09:23,354 --> 00:09:25,899
-My mate Stan. He'll put us up.
-That's only two streets away.

118
00:09:25,982 --> 00:09:29,110
-What about Mo? Where's she living now?
-I don't know. Peak District.

119
00:09:29,194 --> 00:09:30,570
We'll go to cousin Mo's, then.

120
00:09:30,653 --> 00:09:33,031
It's Christmas Eve,
we're not going anywhere.

121
00:09:33,114 --> 00:09:35,658
-What are you babbling about?
-Mum...

122
00:09:36,493 --> 00:09:38,787
Where'd you get that tree?

123
00:09:39,746 --> 00:09:41,664
That's a new tree. Where'd you get it?

124
00:09:41,790 --> 00:09:43,917
-I thought it was you.
-How can it be me?

125
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:46,669
You went shopping, there was a ring
at the door and there it was.

126
00:09:46,795 --> 00:09:48,713
No, that wasn't me.

127
00:09:49,589 --> 00:09:51,966
Then who was it?

128
00:09:55,678 --> 00:09:58,014
Oh, you're kidding me.

129
00:10:10,068 --> 00:10:12,612
MICKEY: Let's go! Quick, get out!

130
00:10:15,031 --> 00:10:17,700
-We've got to save the Doctor.
-What are you doing?

131
00:10:17,826 --> 00:10:19,577
We can't just leave him.

132
00:10:19,661 --> 00:10:20,995
Mickey!

133
00:10:22,038 --> 00:10:24,582
Mickey! Get out, get out!

134
00:10:25,041 --> 00:10:27,794
Mickey! Get out of there.

135
00:10:28,419 --> 00:10:31,339
-No! Leave him, just leave him!
-Get in here.

136
00:10:35,802 --> 00:10:37,470
Doctor, wake up.

137
00:10:44,519 --> 00:10:46,104
(JACKIE SCREAMING)

138
00:10:58,908 --> 00:11:02,120
I'm gonna get killed by a Christmas tree!

139
00:11:05,206 --> 00:11:06,541
Help me.

140
00:11:18,219 --> 00:11:19,637
Remote control.

141
00:11:20,638 --> 00:11:22,432
But who's controlling it?

142
00:11:29,189 --> 00:11:31,774
-That's them. What are they?
-Shh.

143
00:11:49,083 --> 00:11:52,962
They've just gone!
What kind of rubbish were they?

144
00:11:53,046 --> 00:11:54,797
I mean, no offence,
but they're not much cop

145
00:11:54,881 --> 00:11:56,799
if a sonic screwdriver's
gonna scare them off.

146
00:11:56,925 --> 00:11:58,843
-Pilot fish.
-What?

147
00:11:59,969 --> 00:12:01,971
They were just pilot fish.

148
00:12:02,847 --> 00:12:04,849
(GROANING IN PAIN)

149
00:12:04,933 --> 00:12:06,684
What's wrong?

150
00:12:07,602 --> 00:12:09,687
You woke me up too soon.

151
00:12:10,230 --> 00:12:13,066
I'm still regenerating.
I'm bursting with energy.

152
00:12:15,693 --> 00:12:19,530
You see? The pilot fish could smell it
a million miles away.

153
00:12:19,614 --> 00:12:22,700
So they eliminate the defence,
that's you lot, and they carry me off.

154
00:12:22,784 --> 00:12:26,162
They could run their batteries off me
for a couple of years!

155
00:12:26,246 --> 00:12:27,872
Oh, oh, oh!

156
00:12:27,997 --> 00:12:29,415
My head.

157
00:12:29,499 --> 00:12:32,418
-I'm having a neural implosion. I need...
-What do you need?

158
00:12:32,502 --> 00:12:34,045
-I need...
-Just say. Tell me, tell me.

159
00:12:34,128 --> 00:12:35,672
-Painkillers? Aspirin?
-I need...

160
00:12:35,755 --> 00:12:38,591
Codeine? Paracetamol?
Oh, I don't know. Pepto-Bismol?

161
00:12:38,675 --> 00:12:41,594
Liquid paraffin.
Vitamin C, vitamin D, vitamin E!

162
00:12:41,678 --> 00:12:43,930
-I need...
-Is it food? Something simple.

163
00:12:44,013 --> 00:12:45,765
Bowl of soup? Nice bowl of soup?

164
00:12:45,848 --> 00:12:48,393
Soup and a sandwich?
Oh, soup and a little ham sandwich?

165
00:12:48,518 --> 00:12:52,063
-I need you to shut up.
-Oh, he hasn't changed that much.

166
00:12:56,985 --> 00:13:00,530
We haven't got much time.
If there's pilot fish then...

167
00:13:00,655 --> 00:13:02,782
Why is there an apple
in my dressing gown?

168
00:13:02,865 --> 00:13:06,202
-That's Howard, sorry.
-He keeps apples in his dressing gown?

169
00:13:06,327 --> 00:13:08,079
He gets hungry.

170
00:13:08,162 --> 00:13:10,581
-What, he gets hungry in his sleep?
-Sometimes.

171
00:13:13,710 --> 00:13:15,586
Brain collapsing.

172
00:13:17,046 --> 00:13:19,424
The... The pilot fish...

173
00:13:19,549 --> 00:13:22,677
The pilot fish mean there's something...

174
00:13:24,178 --> 00:13:25,722
There's something...

175
00:13:29,851 --> 00:13:31,769
Something is coming.

176
00:13:52,498 --> 00:13:54,834
Jackie, I'm using the phone line,
is that all right?

177
00:13:54,917 --> 00:13:57,211
Yeah, keep account of it.

178
00:13:57,295 --> 00:13:59,005
(CLOCK CHIMES SOFTLY)

179
00:13:59,088 --> 00:14:01,257
It's midnight.

180
00:14:01,341 --> 00:14:03,009
Christmas Day.

181
00:14:03,092 --> 00:14:05,345
-Any change?
-He's worse.

182
00:14:05,428 --> 00:14:06,971
Just one heart beating.

183
00:14:07,055 --> 00:14:09,515
Scientists in charge
of Britain's mission to Mars

184
00:14:09,599 --> 00:14:12,977
have re-established contact with
the Guinevere One space probe.

185
00:14:13,102 --> 00:14:15,188
They're expecting the first transmission

186
00:14:15,271 --> 00:14:17,607
from the planet's surface
in the next few minutes.

187
00:14:17,690 --> 00:14:20,026
Yes, we are. We are back on schedule.

188
00:14:20,109 --> 00:14:23,029
We've received the signal
from Guinevere One.

189
00:14:23,112 --> 00:14:26,949
The Mars landing
would seem to be an unqualified success.

190
00:14:27,033 --> 00:14:30,119
REPORTER: But is it true that
you completely lost contact early tonight?

191
00:14:30,244 --> 00:14:32,705
Yes, we had a bit of a scare.

192
00:14:32,830 --> 00:14:36,459
Guinevere seemed to fall off the scope
but it was just a blip.

193
00:14:36,542 --> 00:14:39,045
Only disappeared for a few seconds.

194
00:14:39,128 --> 00:14:41,589
She is fine now, absolutely fine.

195
00:14:41,672 --> 00:14:45,385
We're getting the first pictures
transmitted live any minute now.

196
00:14:45,468 --> 00:14:47,303
I'd better get back to it. Thanks.

197
00:14:49,180 --> 00:14:51,349
Here we go. Pilot fish.

198
00:14:52,058 --> 00:14:55,144
Scavengers like the Doctor said.
Harmless, they're tiny.

199
00:14:55,269 --> 00:14:58,147
But the point is the little fish
swim alongside the big fish.

200
00:14:58,231 --> 00:15:00,733
-Do you mean like sharks?
-Great, big sharks.

201
00:15:00,817 --> 00:15:04,904
So what the Doctor means is
we had them, now we get that.

202
00:15:04,987 --> 00:15:07,240
Something is coming.

203
00:15:07,323 --> 00:15:10,660
-(ON TV) ...Martian landscape of rocks...
-How close?

204
00:15:10,743 --> 00:15:13,746
There's no way of telling. But the pilot fish
don't swim far from their daddy.

205
00:15:13,830 --> 00:15:16,499
-So it's close.
-Funny sort of rocks.

206
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:19,502
That's not rocks.

207
00:15:19,585 --> 00:15:21,796
(ON TV) This is being transmitted
via Mission Control

208
00:15:21,879 --> 00:15:26,300
and it's coming live from the depths
of space on Christmas morning.

209
00:15:27,510 --> 00:15:29,345
(GROWLING)

210
00:15:31,097 --> 00:15:34,976
The face of an alien life form
was transmitted live tonight on BBC ONE.

211
00:15:35,143 --> 00:15:39,856
On the 25th of December, the human race
has been shown absolute proof

212
00:15:39,939 --> 00:15:41,649
that alien life exists.

213
00:15:41,732 --> 00:15:44,861
These remarkable images
have been relayed right across the world.

214
00:16:08,676 --> 00:16:10,386
This way, sir.

215
00:16:30,990 --> 00:16:32,408
Mr Llewellyn.

216
00:16:33,451 --> 00:16:38,247
MAN: (ON PA) Security sweep at 05176.

217
00:16:38,331 --> 00:16:39,957
Mr Llewellyn, ma'am.

218
00:16:40,041 --> 00:16:43,336
-Harriet Jones, Prime Minister.
-Well, yes, I know who you are.

219
00:16:43,419 --> 00:16:46,631
-I suppose I've ruined your Christmas.
-Never off duty.

220
00:16:46,714 --> 00:16:49,926
Now, we've put out a cover story.
Alex has been handling it.

221
00:16:50,009 --> 00:16:53,387
We've said it was a hoax.
Some sort of mask or prosthetics.

222
00:16:53,471 --> 00:16:55,765
Students hijacking the signal,
that sort of thing.

223
00:16:55,890 --> 00:16:58,809
Alex is my right-hand man.
I'm not used to having a right-hand man.

224
00:16:58,893 --> 00:17:00,686
-I quite like it, though.
-I quite like it myself.

225
00:17:00,770 --> 00:17:03,606
I don't suppose
there's any chance it was a hoax?

226
00:17:03,689 --> 00:17:06,025
That would be nice.
Then we could all go home.

227
00:17:06,108 --> 00:17:08,236
I don't suppose
anyone's offered you a coffee?

228
00:17:08,319 --> 00:17:10,905
-No.
-No, the transmission was genuine.

229
00:17:10,988 --> 00:17:14,116
And this seems to be
a new species of alien.

230
00:17:14,200 --> 00:17:17,119
At least, not one we've encountered before.

231
00:17:17,286 --> 00:17:20,665
You seem to be talking about aliens
as a matter of fact.

232
00:17:20,748 --> 00:17:23,292
There's an Act of Parliament
banning my autobiography.

233
00:17:23,376 --> 00:17:24,961
-Prime Minister?
-I'm with you.

234
00:17:29,423 --> 00:17:31,133
Miss Jacobs can explain.

235
00:17:31,259 --> 00:17:34,053
I don't think we've been introduced.
Harriet Jones, Prime Minister.

236
00:17:34,136 --> 00:17:36,347
Yes. I know who you are.

237
00:17:36,430 --> 00:17:39,517
The transmission didn't come
from the surface of Mars.

238
00:17:39,600 --> 00:17:43,854
Guinevere One was broadcasting
from a point 5,000 miles above the planet.

239
00:17:43,980 --> 00:17:46,857
In other words, they've got a ship
and the probe is onboard.

240
00:17:46,941 --> 00:17:50,611
But if they're not from the surface,
then they might not be from Mars itself.

241
00:17:50,695 --> 00:17:52,905
Maybe they're not actual Martians.

242
00:17:52,989 --> 00:17:55,992
Of course not.
Martians look completely different.

243
00:17:56,117 --> 00:17:59,078
We think the ship was in flight
when they just came across the probe.

244
00:17:59,161 --> 00:18:00,913
And they're moving.

245
00:18:00,997 --> 00:18:04,208
The ship's still in flight now.
We've got it on the Hubble array.

246
00:18:04,333 --> 00:18:07,211
-Moving in which direction?
-Towards us.

247
00:18:07,295 --> 00:18:09,297
-How fast?
-Very fast.

248
00:18:09,380 --> 00:18:11,507
-What was your name again?
-Sally.

249
00:18:13,301 --> 00:18:14,552
Thank you, Sally.

250
00:18:19,390 --> 00:18:20,975
MICKEY: Rose.

251
00:18:21,726 --> 00:18:24,020
Take a look. I've got access to the military.

252
00:18:24,145 --> 00:18:27,481
They're tracking a spaceship.
It's big, it's fast and it's coming this way.

253
00:18:27,565 --> 00:18:30,568
Coming for what, though? The Doctor?

254
00:18:30,693 --> 00:18:33,738
I don't know.
Maybe it's coming for all of us.

255
00:18:33,863 --> 00:18:35,865
(SPEAKING ALIEN LANGUAGE)

256
00:18:40,870 --> 00:18:42,788
Have you seen them before?

257
00:18:43,831 --> 00:18:44,874
No.

258
00:19:00,097 --> 00:19:01,849
Translation software.

259
00:19:02,516 --> 00:19:04,060
Yes, sir.

260
00:19:05,227 --> 00:19:07,063
(ALIENS YELLING)

261
00:19:08,064 --> 00:19:10,149
I don't understand what they're saying.

262
00:19:10,232 --> 00:19:13,444
The Tardis translates alien languages
inside my head

263
00:19:13,569 --> 00:19:16,280
all the time, wherever I am.

264
00:19:16,364 --> 00:19:18,324
So why isn't it doing it now?

265
00:19:19,742 --> 00:19:22,078
I don't know. Must be the Doctor.

266
00:19:23,996 --> 00:19:26,999
Like he's part of the circuit and...

267
00:19:28,084 --> 00:19:29,710
he's broken.

268
00:19:48,813 --> 00:19:51,607
I'm getting demands
from Washington, ma'am.

269
00:19:51,732 --> 00:19:55,194
The President's insisting
that he takes control of the situation.

270
00:19:57,488 --> 00:20:01,242
You can tell the President,
and please use these exact words,

271
00:20:02,076 --> 00:20:05,746
he's not my boss and he's certainly
not turning this into a war.

272
00:20:08,457 --> 00:20:10,584
-What have we got?
-Nothing yet.

273
00:20:10,668 --> 00:20:13,045
Translating an alien language
is going to take time.

274
00:20:13,129 --> 00:20:15,131
How far off is the ship?

275
00:20:15,214 --> 00:20:17,007
About five hours.

276
00:20:18,884 --> 00:20:21,470
Despite claims of an alien hoax,

277
00:20:21,554 --> 00:20:25,099
it's been reported that NATO forces
are on red alert.

278
00:20:25,516 --> 00:20:28,853
Oh, come on, sweetheart.
What do you need?

279
00:20:29,812 --> 00:20:31,981
What is it you need? Tell me.

280
00:20:32,481 --> 00:20:34,900
Speaking strictly off the record,

281
00:20:34,984 --> 00:20:38,362
government sources are calling this
our longest night.

282
00:20:44,660 --> 00:20:47,580
I don't suppose we've had a code 97

283
00:20:47,663 --> 00:20:49,999
-No sign of the Doctor?
-Nothing yet.

284
00:20:51,834 --> 00:20:53,794
You've met him, haven't you?

285
00:20:54,336 --> 00:20:57,173
-Like the stuff of legend.
-He is that.

286
00:20:58,424 --> 00:21:00,426
Failing him...

287
00:21:01,051 --> 00:21:02,511
what about Torchwood?

288
00:21:02,636 --> 00:21:04,847
I know I'm not supposed to know about it,
I realise that.

289
00:21:04,930 --> 00:21:06,640
Not even the United Nations knows.

290
00:21:06,724 --> 00:21:09,351
But if ever there was
a need for Torchwood, it's now.

291
00:21:09,435 --> 00:21:12,188
-I can't take responsibility.
-I can.

292
00:21:13,856 --> 00:21:15,649
See to it. Get them ready.

293
00:21:15,733 --> 00:21:20,237
WOMAN: (ON PA) Attention.
Transmission filters must be maintained...

294
00:21:20,946 --> 00:21:23,866
-Prime Minister.
-Has it worked?

295
00:21:23,949 --> 00:21:25,326
Just about.

296
00:21:27,703 --> 00:21:30,623
"People..." That could be cattle.

297
00:21:30,790 --> 00:21:32,541
"...you belong to us.

298
00:21:32,625 --> 00:21:36,253
"To the Sycorax."” They seem
to be called Sycorax, not Martians.

299
00:21:36,378 --> 00:21:41,509
"We own you. We now possess your land,
your minerals, your precious stones.

300
00:21:41,592 --> 00:21:44,428
"You will surrender or they will die.

301
00:21:44,970 --> 00:21:48,766
"Sycorax strong. Sycorax mighty.
Sycorax rock!"

302
00:21:48,849 --> 00:21:51,185
As in the modern sense, they rock.

303
00:21:51,268 --> 00:21:52,812
"They" will die?

304
00:21:52,895 --> 00:21:55,564
Not "you will die.”
"They will die." Who's they?

305
00:21:55,689 --> 00:21:59,485
I don't know. But it is
the right personal pronoun. It's "they."”

306
00:21:59,568 --> 00:22:02,404
Send them a reply.

307
00:22:02,488 --> 00:22:06,659
Tell them this is a day of peace
on planet Earth.

308
00:22:06,742 --> 00:22:10,704
Tell them we extend that peace
to the Sycorax.

309
00:22:12,581 --> 00:22:14,542
And then tell them

310
00:22:14,625 --> 00:22:18,254
this planet is armed
and we do not surrender.

311
00:22:20,339 --> 00:22:21,674
Come on.

312
00:22:41,068 --> 00:22:43,404
The Doctor wouldn't do this.

313
00:22:43,487 --> 00:22:46,949
The old Doctor, the proper Doctor,
he'd wake up.

314
00:22:47,074 --> 00:22:49,410
He'd save us.

315
00:22:49,493 --> 00:22:51,787
You really love him, don't you?

316
00:23:08,262 --> 00:23:11,390
They got the message.
Here comes the response.

317
00:23:22,151 --> 00:23:24,320
What was that?

318
00:23:24,403 --> 00:23:26,655
-Was that a reply?
-I don't know.

319
00:23:26,739 --> 00:23:29,992
Looked like some sort of energy or static.

320
00:23:30,075 --> 00:23:33,078
Almost like someone casting a spell.

321
00:23:33,162 --> 00:23:34,747
LLEWELLYN: Maybe it's a different form
of language.

322
00:23:34,830 --> 00:23:37,416
Some sort of ideogram or pictogram.

323
00:23:38,083 --> 00:23:39,877
What the hell!

324
00:23:40,711 --> 00:23:43,422
It's the light. It's the same light.

325
00:23:43,547 --> 00:23:46,091
Sally? What are you doing, Sally?

326
00:23:46,175 --> 00:23:47,551
Leave her. You'll hurt her.

327
00:23:47,635 --> 00:23:49,929
-Let them pass.
-Where are they going?

328
00:23:50,638 --> 00:23:52,932
What is wrong with you?

329
00:23:53,015 --> 00:23:54,224
Jason?

330
00:23:55,059 --> 00:23:56,977
-Jason?
-Sandra!

331
00:23:57,561 --> 00:24:01,482
For no reason...he's just walking.
He won't stop walking.

332
00:24:01,857 --> 00:24:05,361
There's a sort of light thing. Jason?

333
00:24:06,028 --> 00:24:08,489
Stop it. Right now.

334
00:24:09,239 --> 00:24:12,034
Please, Jason. Just stop!

335
00:24:16,538 --> 00:24:18,457
They're all heading in the same direction.

336
00:24:18,582 --> 00:24:21,377
It's only certain people.
Why isn't it affecting us?

337
00:24:21,502 --> 00:24:25,089
Prime Minister,
it's happening all over the country.

338
00:24:25,172 --> 00:24:27,591
Alan, come on, now stop this.
It's not funny anymore.

339
00:24:27,675 --> 00:24:29,927
Come on, come back inside the house.

340
00:24:30,010 --> 00:24:32,888
Catherine. Catherine, listen to Mummy.
You come back inside now.

341
00:24:33,013 --> 00:24:36,725
And you, Jonathan.
You come back in with Mummy.

342
00:24:36,850 --> 00:24:40,437
Jonathan, come back in with Mummy.
You're scaring me now. Come on.

343
00:24:40,562 --> 00:24:42,982
Alan, help me out here, please.

344
00:24:45,734 --> 00:24:49,488
As far as I can tell, they're heading for
any sort of high-rise building.

345
00:24:49,571 --> 00:24:51,949
Anything with stairs. Anything with steps.

346
00:25:07,047 --> 00:25:10,092
They're going all the way up.
They're going to the roof.

347
00:25:10,217 --> 00:25:12,302
OFFICER: Just making my way
to the front of the building now.

348
00:25:12,386 --> 00:25:15,264
There's hundreds of them. Oh, my God.

349
00:25:15,347 --> 00:25:18,058
They're going right up to the edge.

350
00:25:18,142 --> 00:25:19,852
They're gonna jump.
They're all gonna jump.

351
00:25:20,102 --> 00:25:21,812
Sally, stop it.

352
00:25:24,314 --> 00:25:26,775
It's Danny Llewellyn. Daniel Llewellyn.

353
00:25:26,859 --> 00:25:29,945
Sally, just concentrate, listen to me.
You're being controlled.

354
00:25:30,029 --> 00:25:31,947
We need you.

355
00:25:32,740 --> 00:25:34,324
Stop it, Sally.

356
00:25:39,747 --> 00:25:43,000
Jason, I'm talking to you! Just stop!

357
00:26:00,100 --> 00:26:02,603
It's not just the whole country.

358
00:26:02,686 --> 00:26:04,813
It's the whole world.

359
00:26:13,322 --> 00:26:16,241
They've stopped. They've all stopped.

360
00:26:16,325 --> 00:26:19,161
They're just standing there.

361
00:26:19,244 --> 00:26:21,205
Right on the edge.

362
00:26:21,330 --> 00:26:25,084
According to reports, it's like a third,
one third of the world's population.

363
00:26:25,167 --> 00:26:27,920
That's two billion people ready to jump.

364
00:26:29,963 --> 00:26:32,216
Surrender or they will die.

365
00:26:33,842 --> 00:26:35,844
What do we do?

366
00:26:36,303 --> 00:26:37,930
Nothing.

367
00:26:38,514 --> 00:26:41,558
There's no one to save us. Not anymore.

368
00:26:44,019 --> 00:26:46,271
Wait a minute. There is a pattern.

369
00:26:46,355 --> 00:26:52,069
All these people tend to be father and son,
mother and daughter, brothers and sisters.

370
00:26:52,194 --> 00:26:54,363
Family groups, but not husbands and wives.

371
00:26:54,446 --> 00:26:56,156
Oh, my God.

372
00:26:56,782 --> 00:26:58,700
It's Guinevere One.

373
00:26:58,784 --> 00:27:01,537
Have you got medical records on file
for all your staff?

374
00:27:01,620 --> 00:27:03,580
Of course we have. Yes.

375
00:27:06,917 --> 00:27:10,712
-What about Torchwood?
-Still working on it.

376
00:27:10,796 --> 00:27:13,215
Bear in mind,
they have just lost a third of their staff.

377
00:27:13,340 --> 00:27:15,843
But do they have what we need?

378
00:27:15,926 --> 00:27:17,719
Yes, ma'am.

379
00:27:17,803 --> 00:27:19,429
Well, tell them to hurry up.

380
00:27:19,513 --> 00:27:23,851
Here it is. Sally Jacobs.
Blood group, A positive.

381
00:27:23,934 --> 00:27:26,603
-Who else walked out?
-Luke Parsons.

382
00:27:26,728 --> 00:27:30,232
Luke Parsons. A positive.

383
00:27:30,315 --> 00:27:32,276
Jeffrey Baxter.

384
00:27:32,401 --> 00:27:34,111
Baxter. A positive.

385
00:27:34,194 --> 00:27:36,613
That's it, they're all A positive.

386
00:27:36,697 --> 00:27:38,615
How many people in the world
are A positive?

387
00:27:38,740 --> 00:27:40,576
No idea.

388
00:27:40,659 --> 00:27:42,411
But I bet it's one third.

389
00:27:42,536 --> 00:27:46,623
-What's so special about that blood group?
-Nothing. But it's my fault.

390
00:27:47,124 --> 00:27:51,295
Guinevere One, it's got one of those
plaques identifying the human race.

391
00:27:51,378 --> 00:27:53,755
A message to the stars.

392
00:27:53,839 --> 00:27:55,924
I mean, you don't expect anything
to come of it

393
00:27:56,008 --> 00:27:58,218
but I put on maps and music and samples.

394
00:27:58,302 --> 00:28:00,762
There's wheat seeds and water and...

395
00:28:01,597 --> 00:28:03,515
And blood.

396
00:28:03,599 --> 00:28:05,559
A positive.

397
00:28:05,642 --> 00:28:09,605
The Sycorax have got a vial of A positive.

398
00:28:10,314 --> 00:28:13,358
And, well, I don't know how,
but through that...

399
00:28:13,442 --> 00:28:15,194
They control the blood.

400
00:28:15,277 --> 00:28:18,280
-Oh, my God.
-There's only one more thing I can try.

401
00:28:18,363 --> 00:28:19,948
Major, with me.

402
00:28:22,701 --> 00:28:27,080
Ladies and gentlemen, if I may take
a moment during this terrible time.

403
00:28:28,498 --> 00:28:32,211
It's hardly the Queen's speech,
I'm afraid that's been cancelled.

404
00:28:33,921 --> 00:28:36,298
Did we ask about the royal family?

405
00:28:38,550 --> 00:28:39,635
Oh.

406
00:28:41,470 --> 00:28:43,263
They're on the roof.

407
00:28:43,805 --> 00:28:47,392
But, ladies and gentlemen,
this crisis is unique,

408
00:28:47,476 --> 00:28:50,979
and I'm afraid to say
it might get much worse.

409
00:28:51,438 --> 00:28:54,149
I would ask you all to remain calm.

410
00:28:55,150 --> 00:28:57,402
But I have one request.

411
00:28:58,111 --> 00:29:00,030
Doctor...

412
00:29:00,155 --> 00:29:03,533
if you're out there, we need you.

413
00:29:05,577 --> 00:29:07,829
I don't know what to do.

414
00:29:08,288 --> 00:29:10,457
If you can hear me, Doctor,

415
00:29:10,540 --> 00:29:13,752
if anyone knows the Doctor,
if anyone can find him,

416
00:29:14,419 --> 00:29:18,048
the situation has never been
more desperate.

417
00:29:19,508 --> 00:29:21,009
Help us.

418
00:29:21,843 --> 00:29:24,513
Please, Doctor, help us.

419
00:29:40,529 --> 00:29:42,197
He's gone.

420
00:29:44,866 --> 00:29:46,827
The Doctor's gone.

421
00:29:47,869 --> 00:29:49,538
He left me, Mum.

422
00:29:51,206 --> 00:29:53,041
He left me, Mum.

423
00:29:58,297 --> 00:29:59,840
Oh, I'm sorry.

424
00:30:11,310 --> 00:30:14,438
Sonic wave! It's the spaceship.
It's hit the atmosphere.

425
00:31:36,353 --> 00:31:38,397
Mickey, we're gonna carry him.

426
00:31:38,480 --> 00:31:40,524
Mum, get your stuff and some food.
We're going.

427
00:31:40,649 --> 00:31:41,900
-Where to?
-The Tardis.

428
00:31:41,983 --> 00:31:43,151
It's the only safe place on Earth.

429
00:31:43,235 --> 00:31:45,070
-What are we going to do in there?
-Hide.

430
00:31:45,153 --> 00:31:47,197
-Is that it?
-Mum, look in the sky.

431
00:31:47,280 --> 00:31:51,368
There's a great, big alien invasion
and I don't know what to do, all right?

432
00:31:51,493 --> 00:31:53,662
I've travelled with him
and I've seen all that stuff,

433
00:31:53,745 --> 00:31:55,956
but when I'm stuck at home, I'm useless.

434
00:31:56,039 --> 00:31:59,835
Now all we can do is run and hide
and I'm sorry.

435
00:31:59,960 --> 00:32:01,628
Now, move.

436
00:32:02,087 --> 00:32:03,505
Lift him up.

437
00:32:04,339 --> 00:32:06,716
They're transmitting on screen.

438
00:32:08,802 --> 00:32:11,304
(SPEAKING ALIEN LANGUAGE)

439
00:32:13,723 --> 00:32:17,269
"Will the leader of this world
stand forward?"

440
00:32:20,188 --> 00:32:22,524
I'm proud to represent this planet.

441
00:32:22,691 --> 00:32:24,401
(SPEAKING ALIEN LANGUAGE)

442
00:32:25,152 --> 00:32:26,862
"Come aboard."”

443
00:32:28,280 --> 00:32:30,031
Well, how do I do that?

444
00:32:32,325 --> 00:32:33,869
What's happening?

445
00:32:35,454 --> 00:32:37,873
I would imagine it's called a teleport.

446
00:32:58,768 --> 00:33:01,563
It's a helmet. They might be like us.

447
00:33:05,901 --> 00:33:07,360
Or not.

448
00:33:07,527 --> 00:33:09,863
(SPEAKING ALIEN LANGUAGE)

449
00:33:19,080 --> 00:33:21,333
Mum, will you just leave that stuff
and give us a hand?

450
00:33:21,416 --> 00:33:23,585
It's food. You said we need...

451
00:33:23,668 --> 00:33:25,212
Just leave it!

452
00:33:29,591 --> 00:33:34,596
"You will surrender
or I will release the final...curse

453
00:33:35,722 --> 00:33:37,265
"and your people will jump.”

454
00:33:38,350 --> 00:33:39,809
If I can speak...

455
00:33:39,893 --> 00:33:41,853
-Mr Llewellyn, you're a civilian.
-No.

456
00:33:41,937 --> 00:33:44,856
I sent out the probe, I started it.
I made contact with these people.

457
00:33:44,940 --> 00:33:47,567
This whole thing's my responsibility.

458
00:33:49,486 --> 00:33:51,446
With respect, sir...

459
00:33:52,614 --> 00:33:57,035
the human race is taking its first steps
towards the stars,

460
00:33:57,118 --> 00:34:00,705
but we are like children compared to you.

461
00:34:00,789 --> 00:34:02,707
Children who need help,

462
00:34:02,791 --> 00:34:05,043
children who need compassion.

463
00:34:06,127 --> 00:34:09,631
I beg of you now, show that compassion.

464
00:34:18,682 --> 00:34:20,725
That man was your prisoner.

465
00:34:20,809 --> 00:34:24,354
Even your species must have
articles of war forbidding...

466
00:34:37,450 --> 00:34:40,120
Harriet Jones, Prime Minister.

467
00:34:42,372 --> 00:34:44,249
"Yes, we know who you are."”

468
00:34:46,167 --> 00:34:48,086
"Surrender or they will die.”

469
00:34:51,006 --> 00:34:54,009
If I do surrender,
how would that be better?

470
00:34:56,553 --> 00:34:59,389
"Half is sold into slavery,

471
00:35:00,015 --> 00:35:01,683
"or one third dies.

472
00:35:05,312 --> 00:35:06,813
"Your choice."

473
00:35:07,606 --> 00:35:08,815
(HISSING)

474
00:35:27,375 --> 00:35:29,586
-No chance you can fly this thing?
-Not anymore, no.

475
00:35:29,669 --> 00:35:31,254
You did it before.

476
00:35:31,338 --> 00:35:34,841
I know, but it's sort of been
wiped out of my head, like it's forbidden.

477
00:35:34,924 --> 00:35:37,469
If I try it again,
I think the universe rips in half.

478
00:35:37,552 --> 00:35:39,387
-Ah. Better not, then.
-Maybe not.

479
00:35:39,471 --> 00:35:42,599
-So what do we do? Just sit here?
-That's as good as it gets.

480
00:35:42,682 --> 00:35:44,267
Right. Here we go.

481
00:35:44,351 --> 00:35:47,270
-Nice cup of tea.
-The solution to everything.

482
00:35:47,395 --> 00:35:50,190
Now stop your moaning.
I'll get the rest of the food.

483
00:35:54,027 --> 00:35:57,530
Tea. Like we're having a picnic
while the world comes to an end.

484
00:35:57,614 --> 00:35:59,491
It's very British.

485
00:36:03,161 --> 00:36:04,829
How does this thing work?

486
00:36:04,913 --> 00:36:07,582
'Cause if it picks up TV, maybe we can see
what's going on out there.

487
00:36:07,666 --> 00:36:09,876
Maybe we've surrendered.
What do you do to it?

488
00:36:09,959 --> 00:36:12,212
I don't know. It sort of tunes itself.

489
00:36:12,295 --> 00:36:14,089
(BEEPING)

490
00:36:21,429 --> 00:36:24,683
The noise, the bleeping.
They say it's machinery.

491
00:36:24,766 --> 00:36:26,101
"Foreign machinery."

492
00:36:26,226 --> 00:36:30,021
They're accusing us of hiding it. Conspiring.

493
00:36:34,776 --> 00:36:36,403
"Bring it on board."

494
00:36:40,281 --> 00:36:41,616
Rose?

495
00:36:44,160 --> 00:36:45,412
Rose!

496
00:36:53,962 --> 00:36:56,965
-Maybe it's a distress signal.
-Fat lot of good that's gonna do.

497
00:36:57,048 --> 00:36:59,217
-Are you gonna be a misery all the time?
-Yes.

498
00:36:59,300 --> 00:37:02,762
You should look at it from my point of view,
stuck in here with your mum's cooking.

499
00:37:02,846 --> 00:37:04,556
Where is she?

500
00:37:04,639 --> 00:37:08,727
I'd better give her a hand.
It might start raining missiles out there.

501
00:37:08,935 --> 00:37:13,106
-Tell her anything from a tin, that's fine.
-Why don't you tell her yourself?

502
00:37:13,231 --> 00:37:15,942
-I'm not that brave.
-Oh, I don't know.

503
00:37:21,865 --> 00:37:23,199
Rose?

504
00:37:24,617 --> 00:37:27,203
ROSE: Get off! Get off me!

505
00:37:29,664 --> 00:37:31,750
The door! Close the door!

506
00:37:33,835 --> 00:37:35,670
MICKEY: Leave her alone!

507
00:37:53,521 --> 00:37:54,939
Rose.

508
00:37:55,023 --> 00:37:56,858
Rose, I've got you.

509
00:37:56,941 --> 00:37:59,194
My Lord. Oh, my precious thing.

510
00:37:59,903 --> 00:38:02,322
The Doctor, is he with you?

511
00:38:03,072 --> 00:38:04,324
No.

512
00:38:05,200 --> 00:38:07,243
We're on our own.

513
00:38:10,914 --> 00:38:12,582
(HISSING)

514
00:38:40,568 --> 00:38:43,947
"The yellow girl,
she has the clever blue box.

515
00:38:44,072 --> 00:38:46,032
"Therefore she speaks for your planet.”

516
00:38:46,157 --> 00:38:48,451
-But, she can't.
-Yeah, I can.

517
00:38:48,910 --> 00:38:51,830
-Don't you dare.
-Someone's got to be the Doctor.

518
00:38:51,913 --> 00:38:54,374
-They'll kill you.
-It never stopped him.

519
00:38:57,418 --> 00:38:59,587
(ALL ROARING)

520
00:39:02,090 --> 00:39:03,716
I, um...

521
00:39:05,093 --> 00:39:07,095
I address the Sycorax...

522
00:39:09,138 --> 00:39:12,767
according to Article 15

523
00:39:12,851 --> 00:39:15,603
of the Shadow Proclamation.

524
00:39:17,021 --> 00:39:19,524
I command you to leave this world

525
00:39:19,607 --> 00:39:22,610
with all the authority of...

526
00:39:22,735 --> 00:39:26,865
the Slitheen Parliament
of Rexicoricophalvitorius

527
00:39:26,948 --> 00:39:29,576
and, um...

528
00:39:29,659 --> 00:39:32,620
the Gelth Confederacy...

529
00:39:32,745 --> 00:39:36,374
as, uh, sanctioned...

530
00:39:36,833 --> 00:39:39,878
by the Mighty Jagrafess and...

531
00:39:39,961 --> 00:39:42,005
Oh! The Daleks.

532
00:39:43,131 --> 00:39:45,633
Now leave this planet in peace!

533
00:39:46,467 --> 00:39:48,094
In peace...

534
00:39:48,177 --> 00:39:50,096
(ALL LAUGHING)

535
00:39:58,146 --> 00:39:59,939
"You are very, very funny."

536
00:40:02,442 --> 00:40:04,444
"And now you're going to die."”

537
00:40:04,527 --> 00:40:06,738
-Leave her alone!
-Don't touch her!

538
00:40:10,366 --> 00:40:12,911
"Did you think you were clever

539
00:40:12,994 --> 00:40:14,787
"with your stolen words?"

540
00:40:17,206 --> 00:40:20,710
"We are the Sycorax
and we stride the darkness.

541
00:40:20,835 --> 00:40:22,337
(GASPING)

542
00:40:22,420 --> 00:40:25,715
"Next to us, you are but a wailing child.

543
00:40:27,842 --> 00:40:32,847
"If you are the best your planet
can offer as a champion..."

544
00:40:32,972 --> 00:40:37,185
(IN ENGLISH) ...then your world
will be gutted...

545
00:40:37,268 --> 00:40:41,022
-and your people enslaved.
-"...and your people enslaved."”

546
00:40:41,814 --> 00:40:44,484
-Hold on, that's English.
-He's talking English.

547
00:40:44,567 --> 00:40:46,110
You're talking English.

548
00:40:46,194 --> 00:40:49,072
I would never dirty my tongue
with your primitive bile!

549
00:40:49,197 --> 00:40:51,449
That's English. Can you hear English?

550
00:40:51,532 --> 00:40:53,326
-Yeah, that's English.
-Definitely English.

551
00:40:53,409 --> 00:40:56,329
I speak only Sycoraxic!

552
00:40:56,412 --> 00:41:00,708
If I can hear English,
then it's being translated.

553
00:41:01,376 --> 00:41:03,211
Which means it's working.

554
00:41:03,294 --> 00:41:04,879
Which means...

555
00:41:12,261 --> 00:41:14,180
Did you miss me?

556
00:41:19,978 --> 00:41:23,398
-You can have someone's eye out with that.
-How dare...

557
00:41:27,652 --> 00:41:30,905
Just can't get the staff. Now, you just wait.

558
00:41:31,072 --> 00:41:32,573
I'm busy.

559
00:41:34,909 --> 00:41:36,703
Mickey, hello!

560
00:41:37,328 --> 00:41:41,082
And Harriet Jones, MP for Flydale North.
Blimey, it's like 7his is Your Life.

561
00:41:41,165 --> 00:41:44,293
Tea! That's all I needed. A good cup of tea.

562
00:41:44,377 --> 00:41:46,671
Super-heated infusion
of free radicals and tannin,

563
00:41:46,754 --> 00:41:48,923
just the thing for healing the synapses.

564
00:41:49,007 --> 00:41:52,635
Now, first things first. Be honest...

565
00:41:53,386 --> 00:41:55,722
-how do I look?
-Um...

566
00:41:56,723 --> 00:41:59,183
-Different.
-Good different or bad different?

567
00:41:59,267 --> 00:42:01,102
Just different.

568
00:42:01,185 --> 00:42:03,938
Am I...ginger?

569
00:42:05,481 --> 00:42:07,734
No, you're just sort of brown.

570
00:42:07,817 --> 00:42:09,861
Oh, I wanted to be ginger.
I've never been ginger.

571
00:42:09,944 --> 00:42:11,654
And you, Rose Tyler,

572
00:42:11,738 --> 00:42:14,949
fat lot of good you were.
You gave up on me. Oh, that's rude.

573
00:42:15,033 --> 00:42:18,494
Is that the sort of man I am now?
Am I rude? Rude and not ginger.

574
00:42:18,578 --> 00:42:21,080
-I'm sorry. Who is this?
-I'm the Doctor.

575
00:42:21,164 --> 00:42:22,415
He's the Doctor.

576
00:42:22,498 --> 00:42:25,793
What happened to my Doctor?
Or is it a title that's just passed on?

577
00:42:25,877 --> 00:42:28,838
I'm him. I'm literally him.

578
00:42:28,921 --> 00:42:31,507
Same man, new face. Well, new everything.

579
00:42:31,591 --> 00:42:34,093
-But you can't be.
-Harriet Jones.

580
00:42:34,177 --> 00:42:36,095
We were trapped in Downing Street

581
00:42:36,179 --> 00:42:39,348
and the one thing that scared you
wasn't the aliens, wasn't the war,

582
00:42:39,432 --> 00:42:41,434
it was the thought of your mother
being on her own.

583
00:42:41,517 --> 00:42:42,977
Oh, my God.

584
00:42:43,061 --> 00:42:46,064
-Did you win the election?
-Landslide majority.

585
00:42:46,147 --> 00:42:48,858
If I might interrupt?

586
00:42:48,983 --> 00:42:50,777
Yes. Sorry. Hello, big fella.

587
00:42:50,860 --> 00:42:54,781
-Who exactly are you?
-Well, that's the question.

588
00:42:54,864 --> 00:42:57,408
I demand to know who you are!

589
00:42:57,492 --> 00:43:00,286
(IMITATING SYCORAX LEADER)
I don't know!

590
00:43:01,370 --> 00:43:05,708
See, that's the thing, I'm the Doctor
but beyond that, I just don't know.

591
00:43:05,792 --> 00:43:09,754
I literally do not know who I am.
It's all untested.

592
00:43:09,837 --> 00:43:12,799
Am I funny? Am I sarcastic?

593
00:43:12,882 --> 00:43:14,092
Sexy?

594
00:43:14,175 --> 00:43:16,719
A right old misery? Life and soul?

595
00:43:16,844 --> 00:43:19,263
Right-handed, left-handed,
a gambler, a fighter,

596
00:43:19,347 --> 00:43:21,933
a coward, a traitor, a liar, a nervous wreck?

597
00:43:22,016 --> 00:43:25,186
I mean, judging by the evidence,
I've certainly got a gob.

598
00:43:25,269 --> 00:43:28,856
And how am I gonna react when I see this?

599
00:43:29,690 --> 00:43:32,944
A great big threatening button.

600
00:43:33,069 --> 00:43:34,445
(DOCTOR LAUGHS)

601
00:43:34,529 --> 00:43:38,825
A great big threatening button which must
not be pressed under any circumstances.

602
00:43:38,908 --> 00:43:40,284
Am I right?

603
00:43:40,368 --> 00:43:42,829
Let me guess,
it's some sort of control matrix. Hmm?

604
00:43:42,912 --> 00:43:44,956
Hold on. What's feeding it?

605
00:43:45,039 --> 00:43:47,125
And what have we got here?

606
00:43:48,126 --> 00:43:49,585
Blood?

607
00:43:49,669 --> 00:43:53,881
Yeah, definitely blood. Human blood.
A positive, with just a dash of iron.

608
00:43:55,216 --> 00:43:57,051
But that means...

609
00:43:57,135 --> 00:43:59,470
Blood control. Blood control!

610
00:43:59,554 --> 00:44:00,972
Oh!

611
00:44:01,055 --> 00:44:03,391
I haven't seen blood control for years!

612
00:44:03,474 --> 00:44:05,685
You're controlling all the A positives.

613
00:44:05,768 --> 00:44:09,105
Which leaves us with
a great big stinking problem,

614
00:44:09,188 --> 00:44:11,899
'cause I really don't know who I am.

615
00:44:12,441 --> 00:44:14,485
I don't know when to stop.

616
00:44:14,569 --> 00:44:17,530
So if I see a great big threatening button

617
00:44:17,613 --> 00:44:19,907
which should never, ever, ever be pressed,

618
00:44:19,991 --> 00:44:22,577
-then I just want to do this.
-No!

619
00:44:30,084 --> 00:44:33,421
-What the hell am I doing up here?
-Get away from the edge.

620
00:44:37,717 --> 00:44:39,969
-You killed them!
-What do you think, big fella?

621
00:44:40,052 --> 00:44:42,388
-Are they dead?
-We allow them to live.

622
00:44:42,471 --> 00:44:45,099
Allow? You've no choice.

623
00:44:45,183 --> 00:44:47,351
That's all blood control is.
Cheap bit of voodoo.

624
00:44:47,435 --> 00:44:49,478
Scares the pants off you
but that's as far as it goes.

625
00:44:49,604 --> 00:44:50,855
It's like hypnosis,

626
00:44:50,938 --> 00:44:53,357
you can hypnotise someone
to walk like a chicken or sing like Elvis,

627
00:44:53,441 --> 00:44:56,444
you can't hypnotise them to death.
Survival instinct's too strong.

628
00:44:56,527 --> 00:45:00,072
Blood control was just
one form of conquest.

629
00:45:00,156 --> 00:45:03,534
I can summon the armada
and take this world by force.

630
00:45:03,618 --> 00:45:05,536
Well, yeah, you could. Yeah.

631
00:45:05,620 --> 00:45:09,123
You could do that, of course you could.
But why?

632
00:45:09,207 --> 00:45:12,293
Look at these people. These human beings.

633
00:45:12,627 --> 00:45:14,795
Consider their potential.

634
00:45:14,879 --> 00:45:19,800
From the day they arrive on the planet
and, blinking, step into the sun,

635
00:45:19,884 --> 00:45:23,262
there is more to see than can ever be seen,

636
00:45:23,346 --> 00:45:25,806
more to do than... No, hold on.

637
00:45:27,600 --> 00:45:31,312
Sorry, that's 7he Lion King.
But the point still stands.

638
00:45:31,771 --> 00:45:34,440
-Leave them alone.
-Or what?

639
00:45:34,523 --> 00:45:35,775
Or...

640
00:45:40,488 --> 00:45:42,156
I challenge you.

641
00:45:42,490 --> 00:45:44,158
(ALL LAUGHING)

642
00:45:45,952 --> 00:45:48,454
Well, that struck a chord.

643
00:45:48,537 --> 00:45:51,999
Am I right that the sanctified rules
of combat still apply?

644
00:45:52,124 --> 00:45:56,671
-You stand as this world's champion?
-Thank you.

645
00:45:57,380 --> 00:46:00,299
I've no idea who I am,
but you've just summed me up.

646
00:46:00,383 --> 00:46:03,928
So, do you accept my challenge?
Or are you just a...

647
00:46:04,011 --> 00:46:06,597
(SPEAKING ALIEN LANGUAGE)

648
00:46:08,099 --> 00:46:10,101
(ALL ROARING)

649
00:46:14,355 --> 00:46:16,774
-For the planet?
-For the planet.

650
00:46:17,900 --> 00:46:20,069
(ALL CHEERING)

651
00:46:29,996 --> 00:46:31,497
(LAUGHING)

652
00:46:42,800 --> 00:46:44,302
Look out!

653
00:46:44,385 --> 00:46:47,930
Oh, yeah, that helps. I wouldn't have
thought of that otherwise. Thanks.

654
00:46:57,732 --> 00:46:59,233
Bit of fresh air?

655
00:47:19,170 --> 00:47:20,629
Stay back!

656
00:47:20,713 --> 00:47:23,257
Invalidate the challenge
and he wins the planet.

657
00:47:47,782 --> 00:47:49,742
You cut my hand off.

658
00:47:49,825 --> 00:47:52,453
Sycorax!

659
00:47:53,996 --> 00:47:56,540
And now I know what sort of man I am.

660
00:47:56,624 --> 00:47:59,585
I'm lucky 'cause quite by chance,

661
00:47:59,668 --> 00:48:02,963
I'm still within the first 15 hours
of my regeneration cycle.

662
00:48:03,089 --> 00:48:06,300
Which means I've got just enough
residual cellular energy

663
00:48:06,425 --> 00:48:08,386
to do this.

664
00:48:15,768 --> 00:48:17,603
Witchcraft.

665
00:48:17,770 --> 00:48:19,772
Time Lord.

666
00:48:21,399 --> 00:48:22,650
Doctor!

667
00:48:25,152 --> 00:48:28,239
-Oh, so I'm still the Doctor, then?
-No arguments from me.

668
00:48:28,322 --> 00:48:30,825
You want to know the best bit?
This new hand...

669
00:48:30,991 --> 00:48:33,244
it's a fighting hand!

670
00:48:45,339 --> 00:48:46,924
(GRUNTING)

671
00:48:47,800 --> 00:48:49,552
(GASPING)

672
00:48:49,677 --> 00:48:50,928
I win.

673
00:48:51,429 --> 00:48:53,222
Then kill me.

674
00:48:53,514 --> 00:48:56,767
I'll spare your life
if you'll take this champion's command.

675
00:48:57,601 --> 00:49:01,188
Leave this planet and never return.

676
00:49:01,981 --> 00:49:04,525
-What do you say?
-Yes.

677
00:49:04,608 --> 00:49:06,986
Swear on the blood of your species.

678
00:49:09,321 --> 00:49:11,782
I swear.

679
00:49:12,366 --> 00:49:14,994
There we are, then. Thanks for that.
Cheers, big fella.

680
00:49:15,077 --> 00:49:16,412
Bravo!

681
00:49:16,537 --> 00:49:19,206
That says it all. Bravo.

682
00:49:19,707 --> 00:49:21,625
Not bad for a man in his jiro jams.

683
00:49:21,709 --> 00:49:24,128
Very Arthur Dent.
Now, there was a nice man.

684
00:49:24,211 --> 00:49:26,422
Hold on, what have I got in here?

685
00:49:26,505 --> 00:49:28,591
A satsuma.

686
00:49:28,716 --> 00:49:31,594
Ah, that friend of your mother's.
He does like his snacks, doesn't he?

687
00:49:31,677 --> 00:49:33,596
But doesn't that just sum up Christmas?

688
00:49:33,721 --> 00:49:36,765
You go through all those presents
and right at the end,

689
00:49:36,891 --> 00:49:40,144
tucked away at the bottom,
there's always one stupid old satsuma.

690
00:49:40,269 --> 00:49:41,979
Who wants a satsuma...

691
00:49:46,734 --> 00:49:48,527
No second chances.

692
00:49:48,736 --> 00:49:50,696
I'm that sort of a man.

693
00:49:57,745 --> 00:50:00,164
By the ancient rites of combat,

694
00:50:00,247 --> 00:50:03,751
I forbid you to scavenge here
for the rest of time.

695
00:50:04,168 --> 00:50:07,922
And when you go back to the stars
and tell others of this planet,

696
00:50:08,005 --> 00:50:13,177
when you tell them of its riches,
its people, its potential,

697
00:50:13,260 --> 00:50:15,846
when you talk of the Earth,

698
00:50:15,930 --> 00:50:18,432
then make sure that you tell them this.

699
00:50:19,308 --> 00:50:22,353
It is defended.

700
00:50:29,777 --> 00:50:33,197
-ROSE: Where are we?
-We're just off Bloxsome Road.

701
00:50:33,280 --> 00:50:35,616
We're just round the corner. We did it!

702
00:50:35,699 --> 00:50:37,785
Wait a minute. Wait a minute.

703
00:50:46,460 --> 00:50:48,921
Go on, my son! Oh, yeah!

704
00:50:49,004 --> 00:50:50,798
Yeah. Don't come back!

705
00:50:50,881 --> 00:50:53,259
It is defended!

706
00:51:04,436 --> 00:51:07,147
-My Doctor.
-Prime Minister.

707
00:51:11,485 --> 00:51:13,737
Absolutely the same man.

708
00:51:18,492 --> 00:51:22,955
-Are there many more out there?
-Ooh, not just Sycorax.

709
00:51:24,164 --> 00:51:26,166
Hundreds of species.

710
00:51:26,250 --> 00:51:28,002
Thousands of them.

711
00:51:28,836 --> 00:51:32,131
And the human race
is drawing attention to itself.

712
00:51:32,214 --> 00:51:36,844
Everyday you're sending out probes,
messages and signals.

713
00:51:36,927 --> 00:51:38,846
This planet's so noisy.

714
00:51:39,972 --> 00:51:43,684
You're getting noticed, more and more.

715
00:51:45,686 --> 00:51:47,855
You better get used to it.

716
00:51:48,272 --> 00:51:49,565
-Rose!
-Mum.

717
00:51:49,648 --> 00:51:51,150
Talking of trouble...

718
00:51:51,233 --> 00:51:53,736
-Oh, my God! Rose.
-He did it, Mum.

719
00:51:53,861 --> 00:51:55,446
(MOBILE RINGING)

720
00:51:55,529 --> 00:51:58,282
You did it, too!
It was the tea. Fixed his head.

721
00:51:58,365 --> 00:52:00,075
That's all I needed. Cup of tea.

722
00:52:00,200 --> 00:52:02,328
-I said so.
-And look at him.

723
00:52:02,411 --> 00:52:05,706
Is it him, though? Is it really the Doctor?

724
00:52:08,083 --> 00:52:11,128
Oh, my God!
It's the bleeding Prime Minister!

725
00:52:11,211 --> 00:52:12,630
Come here, you.

726
00:52:16,383 --> 00:52:18,302
JACKIE: Are you better?

727
00:52:21,221 --> 00:52:25,726
It's a message from Torchwood.
They say they're ready.

728
00:52:30,272 --> 00:52:31,815
JACKIE: You left me.

729
00:52:31,940 --> 00:52:33,901
What do I do with the food?

730
00:52:36,070 --> 00:52:37,905
Tell them to fire.

731
00:52:42,618 --> 00:52:44,078
Fire at will.

732
00:53:19,154 --> 00:53:21,615
What is that? What's happening?

733
00:53:28,622 --> 00:53:31,291
-That was murder.
-That was defence.

734
00:53:31,375 --> 00:53:33,919
It's adapted from alien technology.

735
00:53:34,294 --> 00:53:37,715
-A ship that fell to Earth ten years ago.
-But they were leaving.

736
00:53:37,798 --> 00:53:40,718
You said yourself, Doctor,
they'd go back to the stars

737
00:53:40,801 --> 00:53:43,137
and tell others about the Earth.

738
00:53:43,262 --> 00:53:46,306
I'm sorry, Doctor, but you're not here
all the time. You come and go.

739
00:53:46,432 --> 00:53:50,060
It happened today.
Mr Llewellyn and the Major.

740
00:53:50,185 --> 00:53:53,981
They were murdered. They died right
in front of me while you were sleeping.

741
00:53:54,064 --> 00:53:56,900
In which case, we have to defend ourselves.

742
00:53:56,984 --> 00:53:59,820
-Britain's golden age.
-It comes with a price.

743
00:53:59,903 --> 00:54:02,281
I gave them the wrong warning.

744
00:54:02,364 --> 00:54:05,075
I should have told them
to run as fast as they can.

745
00:54:05,159 --> 00:54:08,412
Run and hide because the monsters
are coming. The human race.

746
00:54:08,495 --> 00:54:11,665
Those are the people I represent.
I did it on their behalf.

747
00:54:11,790 --> 00:54:13,375
And I should have stopped you.

748
00:54:13,500 --> 00:54:17,546
What does that make you, Doctor?
Another alien threat?

749
00:54:17,671 --> 00:54:21,967
Don't challenge me, Harriet Jones,
"cause I'm a completely new man.

750
00:54:22,676 --> 00:54:25,345
I could bring down your government
with a single word.

751
00:54:25,429 --> 00:54:28,807
You're the most remarkable man
I've ever met,

752
00:54:30,267 --> 00:54:32,978
but I don't think
you're quite capable of that.

753
00:54:33,061 --> 00:54:35,189
No. You're right. Not a single word.

754
00:54:37,399 --> 00:54:39,443
-Just six.
-I don't think so.

755
00:54:39,526 --> 00:54:41,195
-Six words.
-Stop it.

756
00:54:41,278 --> 00:54:42,738
Six.

757
00:54:54,041 --> 00:54:56,460
Don't you think she looks tired?

758
00:55:10,933 --> 00:55:12,893
-What did he say?
-Nothing, really.

759
00:55:13,018 --> 00:55:15,646
-What did he say?
-Nothing. I don't know.

760
00:55:15,729 --> 00:55:17,439
Doctor!

761
00:55:17,523 --> 00:55:19,525
Doctor, what did... What was that?
What did he say?

762
00:55:19,608 --> 00:55:22,236
What did you say, Doctor? Doctor!

763
00:55:26,698 --> 00:55:28,200
I'm sorry.

764
00:57:00,667 --> 00:57:02,294
Oh, that's yours.

765
00:57:03,670 --> 00:57:07,049
It's pink! It should be yours.

766
00:57:09,301 --> 00:57:11,094
Look, it's Harriet Jones.

767
00:57:11,178 --> 00:57:14,097
REPORTER: Prime Minister, is it true
you're no longer fit to be in position?

768
00:57:14,181 --> 00:57:16,683
No. Now, can we talk about other things?

769
00:57:16,767 --> 00:57:18,644
Is it true you're unfit for office?

770
00:57:18,727 --> 00:57:21,271
Look, there is nothing wrong
with my health.

771
00:57:21,355 --> 00:57:24,399
I don't know where these stories
are coming from.

772
00:57:24,483 --> 00:57:27,319
And a vote of no confidence
ls completely unjustified.

773
00:57:27,402 --> 00:57:28,987
Are you going to resign?

774
00:57:29,112 --> 00:57:33,867
On today of all days, I find I'm fine.
Look at me, I'm fine. I look fine, I feel fine.

775
00:57:33,951 --> 00:57:36,787
-It's Bev. She says go and look outside.
-Why?

776
00:57:36,870 --> 00:57:39,539
I don't know. Just go outside and look.
Come on, shift.

777
00:57:54,054 --> 00:57:55,931
That's beautiful.

778
00:57:56,056 --> 00:57:57,724
What are they? Meteors?

779
00:57:57,808 --> 00:58:00,894
It's the spaceship
breaking up in the atmosphere.

780
00:58:01,728 --> 00:58:04,147
This isn't snow. It's ash.

781
00:58:04,231 --> 00:58:06,274
Okay, not so beautiful.

782
00:58:07,401 --> 00:58:09,778
And this is a brand-new planet Earth.

783
00:58:10,821 --> 00:58:14,032
No denying the existence of aliens now.
Everyone saw it.

784
00:58:14,825 --> 00:58:16,243
Everything's new.

785
00:58:16,326 --> 00:58:19,079
And what about you?
What are you gonna do next?

786
00:58:19,871 --> 00:58:21,707
Well...

787
00:58:22,916 --> 00:58:25,419
back to the Tardis, same old life.

788
00:58:26,628 --> 00:58:28,922
-On your own?
-Why, don't you want to come?

789
00:58:29,006 --> 00:58:30,424
-Well, yeah.
-Do you?

790
00:58:30,549 --> 00:58:32,718
-Yeah.
-Well, I just thought...

791
00:58:32,801 --> 00:58:36,054
-'cause I'd changed.
-Yeah, I thought 'cause you'd changed...

792
00:58:36,138 --> 00:58:37,848
you might not want me anymore.

793
00:58:37,931 --> 00:58:39,975
-Oh, I'd love you to come.
-Okay.

794
00:58:40,058 --> 00:58:42,352
You're never gonna stay, are you?

795
00:58:44,604 --> 00:58:46,732
There's just so much out there.

796
00:58:46,857 --> 00:58:49,860
So much to see. I've got to.

797
00:58:50,944 --> 00:58:52,529
Yeah.

798
00:58:52,612 --> 00:58:55,532
Well, I reckon you're mad. The pair of you.

799
00:58:55,615 --> 00:58:59,870
-It's like you go looking for trouble.
-Trouble's just the bits in-between.

800
00:58:59,953 --> 00:59:02,247
It's all waiting out there, Jackie.

801
00:59:02,372 --> 00:59:04,374
And it's brand-new to me.

802
00:59:04,458 --> 00:59:09,629
All those planets, creatures and horizons,
haven't seen them yet.

803
00:59:10,047 --> 00:59:11,673
Not with these eyes.

804
00:59:13,467 --> 00:59:15,260
And it is gonna be...

805
00:59:17,512 --> 00:59:19,139
fantastic.

806
00:59:22,225 --> 00:59:25,145
That hand of yours
still gives me the creeps.

807
00:59:35,113 --> 00:59:37,240
So, where are we gonna go first?

808
00:59:37,824 --> 00:59:39,034
Um...

809
00:59:40,660 --> 00:59:42,746
That way. No, hold on.

810
00:59:45,332 --> 00:59:47,584
-That way.
-That way.

811
00:59:47,667 --> 00:59:49,044
You think?

812
00:59:49,836 --> 00:59:51,505
Yeah. That way.

813
01:00:02,682 --> 01:00:06,186
-So, where are we going?
-Further than we've ever gone before.

814
01:00:07,020 --> 01:00:08,355
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

815
01:00:09,189 --> 01:00:11,525
-I don't believe we've met.
-I'm the Doctor.

816
01:00:11,650 --> 01:00:13,985
May I introduce Miss Sarah Jane Smith?

817
01:00:19,324 --> 01:00:20,992
DOCTOR: K-9!

818
01:00:24,621 --> 01:00:27,999
Said he'll talk to a wanderer.
To the man without a home.

819
01:00:28,500 --> 01:00:31,545
Might I introduce
Her Majesty, Queen Victoria?

820
01:00:31,670 --> 01:00:33,380
Give her back to me.

821
01:00:37,050 --> 01:00:38,593
Bullets can't stop it.

